@Node Install "Installation - Miami Start/Stop - Miami Online/Offline/Online Details/Program Launcher with GUI"
@{fg highlight}@{b}Installation:@{ub}@{fg text}

To get Miami Start/Stop running without fuss, just run the program from CLI/Shell or use the Icon (MSS) that calls IconX.

If you want to make Miami Start/Stop do more then just get online/offline and tell you simple online time.  Then read below.


To get Miami Start/Stop working right, you might want to run the MSSPrefs Program.

Suggested place of installing MSSPrefs is in the same Dir as MiamiStartStop, Miami: or SYS:Prefs/

MSSPrefs allows you to Set a Miami Phone Log, which lets you work around a bug in Miami's before v3.0d.  It will let you set the Miami Log File, so Miami Start/Stop can keep track of Online time even of you reset. This also allows you to monitor amount of Connects, ReConnect [usually caused by a reset/crash], Passive offlines [Booted off by your IP or you lost carrier], Active offlines [you disconnected] and averages of the daily information and much more.

I suggest @{b}highly@{ub} you active the the Miami Phone Log and use it.  To do so, simply open your Miami program GUI, choose on the left hand side listview: Logging.  Go to the Phone Log section (second part of the three in Miami v3) on that page.  Change the Cycle gadget to ASCII, then type in Miami:Miami.PhoneLog in the string gadget above that cycle gadget.  The String you enter can be anywhere really, but it is best that you do it on a place that is reset proof and will last when you switch off your computer, EG: Where you Miami Assign is.  Save your Miami Preferences.  Once you have Reconnected or made a new connection (IE Reset and reconnected or dropped carrier and reconnected to your Internet account), then open up MSSPrefs and select the file you entered in the Miami string gadget prior and then save your MSSPrefs.

MSSPrefs allows you to set Online Internet costs.  This allows you to set $ or Ł or anything else as your money note.  It also lets you set a per minute rate and from what time online it starts to take effect. Example: Pay 0.25 per minute after 180 minutes (this is 3 hours) online.

MSSPrefs saves its data to ENV:MSS_Prefs and also ENVARC:MSS_Prefs
You can alter them by hand yourself, but is definately suggested you avoid doing so.  I suggest you use the enclosed MSSPrefs program.


Miami Start/Stop allows you run programs once its online (@{u}automatically or at your own choice@{uu}) when you run Miami Start/Stop and get online or from the GUI.  To do this put the full programs path and arguements in the file ENV:MSS_Startup and ENVARC:MSS_Startup and will run these without any hassles.  Or you can also make your own one anywhere on you system and use the @{" Startup " link Using 0000} option.

Example contents of "ENV:MSS_Startup" would look like:

YAM:YAM
Comms:AmIRC/AmIRC
GlenMartin:IsMost/Hated/InOz

It will CD to the programs directory for full program compatibility
(Ala Rexx Scripts with AmIRC, etc)
Then it executes the program with a 32000 Stack (So no running out of Stack)

@Endnode
@Node Using "Usage - Miami Start/Stop - Miami Online/Offline/Online Details/Program Launcher with GUI"
@{fg highlight}@{b}Usage:@{ub}@{fg text}

MiamiStartStop [Config File] [Always/GUI] [NoStartup] [Starup=<StartFile>] [NotAutoOnline/NAO] [Time=<TimeInSeconds>] [Expert] [HELP/?]

[Config File]   - this is optional, and will not affect Miami Start/Stop from realising that Miami is running or is online to shut it down if necessary.

[MiamiExe]   - this is to specify the executable you want to use as the Miami executable.  To use MiamiDeluxe as the executable: MiamiStartStop MiamiExe=MiamiDx.beta

[Always or GUI]   - this lets you have the GUI always there will all functions of Miami Start/Stop available to you.

[Starup=<StartFile>]   - this lets you specify a text file that will run once Miami is online.  By defalt it will attempt to run the contents of ENV:MSS_Startup file

[NoStartup]   - this forces Miami Start/Stop so it won't use any Startup file (Even if the Startup argument was given)

[GoStart or RunStart]   - this runs the Startup file straight away if Miami is online already.

[Shutdown=<ShutdownFile>]   - this use the file to load programs & send ARexx commands.
                               EG: MiamiStartStop Shutdown=ENV:MSS_Kill_2

[NoShutdown]   - this will not use any Shutdown file to load programs & send ARexx commands.
                         It overrides ENV:MSS_Shutdown and the Shutdown argument.

[GoShut or RunShut]   - Will run the Shutdown file straight away.

[Time=<TimeInSeconds>]   - this allows the user define a delay between starting of programs in seconds.  (Default is 5 Seconds)

[Wait=<TimeInSeconds>]   - this allows the user define an amount of time to wait for Miami to get online in seconds.  Default is 60 Seconds.  Minimum is 20 seconds.  Maximum is 3600 seconds (60 Minutes).

[NotAutoOnline or NAO]   - this goes to the Online Menu of MSS after loading Miami so you can alter your Miami Preferences, Control MSS/Miami manually, etc.

[NoVerify]   - this will remove the pop-up requestor to make sure(verify) if you hit any of the Disconnect/Quit/Force Quit buttons.
              (Will @{b}REMOVE@{ub} he make sure(verify) if you wish to Disconnect/Quit/Force Quit.)

[Expert]   - this will remove the general button information above the buttons (Expert menus).

[Details]   - this will show you Miami's Online Details if you are online.

[Sync=<Number>]   - this will let you choose a way to load the Miami phone log (a-)synchronously.
                     EG:
                      Sync=0 (Default) will load the file A-Sychronously(Good for fast Harddrives [or AFS/PFS2/SFS users]).
                      Sync=1 will load the file Synchronously (General use Sync).
                      Sync=2 will load the file Synchronously(Best for Very fast CPUs & Very slow HDs)
                     Note: It will load the whole logfile into memory before working on it.

[Online]   - this will put Miami online of you are not online already.

[Offline]   - this will take Miami offline with warnings if you are online.

[Quit]   - this will quit Miami with warnings if it is running.

[ForceQuit]   - Will force quit Miami with warnings if it is running.

[Lock]   - this will lock the Miami GUI (making the pointer busy).

[UnLock]   - this will unlock the Miami GUI (making the pointer not busy).

[KillGUI]   - this will release Miami's current GUI library so you can flush it, saving memory.

[DialGUI or ShowDial]   - this shows the Miami GUI whilst trying to get online.

[LargeGUI]   - this shows all the extra menu options at once at the expense of screen space.

[ReConnect=<TimeInSeconds>]   - this lets you supply a delay (in seconds) before attempting to reconnect
                                   EG: MiamiStartStop ReConnect=900   - ReConnects Miami after 900 seconds [15 Minutes]

[HELP or ?]   - Brings up the inbuilt help information.


Example:

MiamiStartStop Miami:InternetAccount1 Always Startup=ENV:Startup_Account2

This will use Miami with the config file "Miami:InternetAccount1".  If Miami is already online, it will ask if you wish to go Offline or Quit (and go Offline) Miami.  The Startup file will run all the files listed in ENV:Startup_Account2

**NOTE:
If you plan to use it from an Icon on Workbench, please edit the MSS file with your favourite text editor.  The command options are the same as above. @{fg highlight}@{b}NOTE:  If loading from workbench use the MSS Icon that uses IconX!!  @{u}DO NOT@{uu} load from workbench without using IconX!@{ub}@{fg text}

Miami Start/Stop allows you run programs once its online (automatically or at your own choice) when you run Miami Start/Stop and get online or from the GUI.  To do this put the full programs path and arguements in the file ENV:MSS_Startup and ENVARC:MSS_Startup and will run these without an arguement telling it to do so.  Or you can also make your own one anywhere on you system and use the @{" Startup " link Using 0000} option.

Example contents of "ENV:MSS_Startup" would look like:

YAM:YAM
Comms:AmIRC/AmIRC
GlenMartin:RimJobs/RoadKill

It will CD to the programs directory for full program compatibility (Ala Rexx Scripts with AmIRC, etc) Then it executes the program with a 32000 Stack (So no running out of Stack)


It's easy to use and powerful, so just have fun with it. :)

@Endnode
@Node StartStop "Startup/Shutdown - Miami Start/Stop - Miami Online/Offline/Online Details/Program Launcher with GUI"
@{fg highlight}@{b}Startup/Shutdown:@{ub}@{fg text}

Miami Start/Stop v2.50+ introduces it's own programming language.  Before you sit there and think it is impossible for you to program, this programming language was made for people who are limited in their ability.  And to make certain tasks very easy.  This programming language allows Miami Start/Stop to run programs on startup, control them or shut them down.
other programs as well, using Miami Start/Stop.

For execution of an external program or Arexx command to a program:

IF <ARexx Port> <Exists/NoExists> <AREXX/Program> <AREXX Command>

Example 1:

IF IBROWSE NOEXISTS DH1:IBrowse/IBrowse

If IBrowse isn't running then run it. Just replace DH1:IBrowse/IBrowse with the path and filename of where IBrowse is.


Example 2:

IF AMIRC.1 EXISTS AREXX QUIT

If AmIRC was running it would shut it down (Only AMIRC.1 which is what the program calls the first instance of itself).  You can have as many copies of AmIRC running as you want.


Example 3:

IF AMIRC.x EXISTS AREXX QUIT

This will shut down all running copies of AmIRC.


Example 4:

IF AMIRC.1 NOEXISTS DH1:AmIRC/AmIRC Connect server=sydney.oz.org port=6668 Autojoin=#AmigaZone

If Amirc is not running, this tells it to connect to the server sydney.oz.org on port 6668 and automatically join the channel #AmigaZone.


Example 5:

YAM:YAM

This will run YAM in YAM: (assign by YAM when it's installed) without checking for any ARexx ports.


Example 6:

;Instead you can do: IF YAM NOEXISTS YAM:YAM

This will be treated as a comment because of the ';' at the start of hte line.  It will only treat it as a comment if ';' is at the start of the line.

@Endnode
@Node QandA "FAQ - Miami Start/Stop - Miami Online/Offline/Online Details/Program Launcher with GUI"
@{fg highlight}@{b}FAQ (Frequently Asked Questions):@{ub}@{fg text}

Q) Why use the Miami Phone Log and make your own logfile of logon and logoff?

A) Speed, more information and more accurate times.  Miami has a Phone Log inbuilt for for a good reason, to analyse the past actions of Miami in a fast form.  Doing it not via Miami slows your computer down by repeated checks and the repeated storing of the data.  For this reason I suggest not using such programs.


Q) Why a did it used to be a self executing program?  Why not an ARexx Script?

A) Basicaly all programmers are sick of seeing their hard work stolen or
   hacked or used in a wrong manner.  With various dumb kids around I
   made it Executeable for protection of my code and so it won't have
   backdoors by the average Joe Schmoe.  Everyone also wants something
   like this as I have seen on various mailing lists.


Q) Why now a ARexx script, when ya were against it in the past?

A) In the past I could, unfortunately the ARexx limit is 64k of making a self executing ARexx script.  So I have to either limi it below 64k or release it as an ARexx script.  So here is the source. :)


Q) Miami Start/Stop Crashes when I Quit when I run it from workbench, WHY?!

A) This is because you didn't use the Icon in the archive, the program
   needs to be run from IconX as the Compiler doesn't like to be run
   directly from workbench.  I am trying to rectify this with getting a
   better compiler.


Q) Where does Miami Start/Stop need to be installed?

A) Anywhere you like.  It's location on your harddrive makes no difference.
   If you run it from workbench it is suggested you keep the program
   MiamiStartStop and MSS and MSS.info all in the same dir.  I suggest
   Miami: assign (created by Miami when it is installed).


Q) Why is Miami Start/Stop not accurate to my phone bill although I have
   entered everything correctly?

A) If you have the correct phone log pointed to, then it's likely to be a
   case of Miami not always saving the data if loose connection after you
   crash as Miami saves the data for Miami Start/Stop to analyse.  This
   would affect the calculations greatly.  Also some phone networks have
   been 'ripping off' customers of their service and it is near enough
   impossible to prove it in a court of law here in Australia
   (and possibly elsewhere) even with approved counters/timers, etc.
   So there is various reasons it may not be perfect but I have written
   Miami Start/Stop to deal with as much as possible and to be as perfect
   as possible in all situations.
   (I am not perfect I know, but it should be close at least ;)


Q) I want an addition to Miami Start/Stop, can I offer ideas, or ways to
   improve it?

A) Yes, I will acknowledge you fully and improve the program for sure.  At the current stage certain ideas and implementation is taking time due to the source complexity of Miami Start/Stop.


Q) Could you write me a ARexx script or program to do something for me?

A) Yes, just ask.  I am always looking for something new on peoples screens.


Q) I have a problem not mentioned here, what should I do?

A) EMail me at:  sykoe@sub.net.au
            or:  lanky@connect.net.au
   ICQ me on:  12298533

@Endnode
